Creating a drag-and-drop Kanban board in React involves several steps. You'll need to use a state management system like Redux or Context API to manage the board's state, as well as a library like react-beautiful-dnd to handle the drag-and-drop functionality. Below is a basic example to get you started.

1. **Set Up Your React Project**:
   If you haven't already, create a new React project using Create React App:
   ```sh
   npx create-react-app kanban-board
   cd kanban-board
   npm install react-beautiful-dnd
   ```

2. **Create the Kanban Board Structure**:
   Create a folder structure for your app:
   ```
   src/
   ├── components/
   │   ├── KanbanBoard.js
   │   ├── Column.js
   │   └── Task.js
   └── App.js
   ```

3. **Implement the Task Component**:
   Create a `Task.js` component to represent individual tasks.
   ```jsx
   // Task.js
   import React from 'react';

   const Task = ({ task }) => {
     return (
       <div className="task">
         {task.content}
       </div>
     );
   };

   export default Task;
   ```

4. **Implement the Column Component**:
   Create a `Column.js` component to represent a column.
   ```jsx
   // Column.js
   import React from 'react';
   import { Draggable } from 'react-beautiful-dnd';
   import Task from './Task';

   const Column = ({ column, index, onDrop, onReorder }) => {
     return (
       <div className="column">
         <h2>{column.title}</h2>
         <div className="tasks">
           {column.tasks.map((task, i) => (
             <Draggable key={task.id} draggableId={task.id} index={i} onDragEnd={(result) => onReorder(result, i)}>
               <div>
                 <Task task={task} />
               </div>
             </Draggable>
           ))}
         </div>
       </div>
     );
   };

   export default Column;
   ```

5. **Implement the KanbanBoard Component**:
   Create the `KanbanBoard.js` component that manages the state and renders the columns.
   ```jsx
   // KanbanBoard.js
   import React, { useState } from 'react';
   import { DragDropContext, Droppable } from 'react-beautiful-dnd';
   import Column from './Column';

   const KanbanBoard = () => {
     const [columns, setColumns] = useState([
       { title: 'To Do', id: 1, tasks: [] },
       { title: 'In Progress', id: 2, tasks: [] },
       { title: 'Done', id: 3, tasks: [] }
     ]);

     const handleReorder = (result, i) => {
       if (!result.destination) return;

       const { source, destination } = result;
       const column = columns[source.destination.index];

       // Swap tasks
       const newTasks = Array.from(column.tasks);
       const [taskToMove] = newTasks.splice(source.index, 1);
       newTasks.splice(destination.index, 0, taskToMove);

       const newColumn = { ...column, tasks: newTasks };
       const newColumns = [...columns];
       newColumns[destination.destination.index] = newColumn;

       setColumns(newColumns);
     };

     // Function to handle the completion of the drag and drop
     const handleOnDragEnd = (result) => {
       if (!result.destination) return;

       const { source, destination } = result;
       const sourceColumn = columns[source.index];
       const destColumn = columns[destination.index];

       // Remove from the source and add to the destination
       const newTask = sourceColumn.tasks.pop();
       columns[source.index].tasks = sourceColumn.tasks;
       columns[destination.index].tasks.push({ id: newTask.id, content: newTask.content });

       setColumns(columns);
     };

     return (
       <DragDropContext onDragEnd={(result) => handleOnDragEnd(result)}>
         {columns.map((column, index) => (
           <Droppable key={column.id} droppableId={column.id}>
             {(provided, snapshot) => (
               <Column
                 column={column}
                 index={index}
                 onDrop={handleDrop}
                 onReorder={handleReorder}
                 ref={provided.innerRef}
                 isDropDisabled={!snapshot.isDropDisabled}
               />
             )}
           </Droppable>
         ))}
       </DragDropContext>
     );
   };

   export default KanbanBoard;
   ```

6. **Style Your Components**:
   You can add CSS to style your components. Here is a basic example:
   ```css
