Understood! Please describe the functionality of the Chrome extension you would like to build, and I'll provide a comprehensive how-to guide with detailed code and explanations.

### Step-by-Step Guide to Building a Chrome Extension

---

**Introduction:**

In this guide, we will build a basic Chrome extension that interacts with a weather API to display the current weather information of the user's location. The extension will consist of the following components:

1. Manifest file (`manifest.json`)
2. Background/service worker script (`service_worker.js`)
3. Content script (`content_script.js`)
4. Popup HTML and JavaScript (`popup/popup.html` and `popup/popup.js`)
5. Options page HTML and JavaScript (`options/options.html` and `options/options.js`)
6. Icons for the extension

---

### 1. Manifest File (`manifest.json`)

The `manifest.json` file provides important details about the extension to Chrome. This file is used to define permissions, background scripts, content scripts, and popup files.

```json
{
  "manifest_version": 3,
  "name": "Weather extension",
  "version": "1.0",
  "description": "Get the current weather information for your location.",
  "action": {
    "default_popup": "popup/popup.html",
    "default_icon": "icons/icon_48.png"
  },
  "background": {
    "service_worker": "service_worker.js"
  },
  "permissions": [
    "geolocation",
    "storage",
    "activeTab"
  ],
  "content_scripts": [
    {
      "matches": ["http://*/*", "https://*/*"],
      "js": ["content_script.js"]
    }
  ],
  "options_page": "options/options.html",
  "icons": {
    "48": "icons/icon_48.png",
    "128": "icons/icon_128.png"
  }
}
```

### 2. Service Worker Script (`service_worker.js`)

The service worker is responsible for handling background tasks and responding to browser actions. For our weather extension, we'll use it to fetch weather data.

```javascript
// service_worker.js

// Constants for the weather API endpoint
const apiUrl = 'https://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/weather';
const apiKey = 'YOUR_OPENWEATHERMAP_API_KEY'; // Replace with your actual API key

// Function to get weather data based on the user's location
async function getWeather(lat, lon) {
  try {
    const response = await fetch(`${apiUrl}?lat=${lat}&lon=${lon}&appid=${apiKey}&units=metric`);
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error('Network response was not ok');
    }
    return await response.json();
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Fetch error:', error);
  }
}

// Event listeners for browser actions
chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener((request, sender, sendResponse) => {
  if (request.action === 'getWeatherData') {
    navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(async (position) => {
      const weatherData = await getWeather(position.coords.latitude, position.coords.longitude);
      sendResponse(weatherData);
    }, (error) => {
      console.error('Geolocation Error:', error);
      sendResponse(null);
    });
    // No need to send a response immediately, but the asynchronous call will resolve this listener
    return true;
  }
});
```

### 3. Content Script (`content_script.js`)

A content script can interact with web pages and inject our weather data. For simplicity, we'll just log the weather data to the console.

```javascript
// content_script.js

// Listen for messages from the background script
chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener((request, sender, sendResponse) => {
  if (request.action === 'displayWeather') {
    // Display weather data in a popup (for demo purposes, we're just logging to the console)
    console.log('Weather:', request.weather);
  }
});
```

### 4. Popup HTML & JavaScript (`popup/popup.html` and `popup/popup.js`)

The popup will be the UI that the user interacts with when they click on the extension icon.

#### `popup/popup.html`

```html
<!-- popup/popup.html -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Weather Extension</title>
  <style>
    body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; margin: 10px; }
    .weather { margin-top: 10px; }
    .temperature { font-size: 2em; }
    .weather-description { font-size: 1.2em; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Current Weather</h1>
  <div class="temperature" id="temperature"></div>
  <div class="weather-description" id="description"></div>
  <script src="popup.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

#### `popup/popup.js`

```javascript
// popup/popup.js

document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', async () => {
  // Fetch weather data from the background script
  const [weather] = await Promise.all([
    chrome.runtime.sendMessage({ action: 'getWeatherData' })
  ]);

  // If weather data is available, display it in the UI
  if (weather) {
    document.getElementById('temperature').textContent = `${weather.main.temp} °C`;
    document.getElementById('description').textContent = weather.weather[0].description;
    // Send weather data to the content script
    chrome.tabs.query({ active: true, currentWindow: true }, (tabs) => {
      chrome.tabs.sendMessage(tabs[0].id, { action: 'displayWeather', weather });
    });
  } else {
    console.error('No weather data available');
  }
});
```

### 5. Options Page HTML & JavaScript (`options/options.html` and `options/options.js`)

This provides a page for the user to configure options for the extension.

#### `options/options.html`

```html
<!-- options/options.html -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Options</title>
  <style>
    body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; margin: 10px; }
    input { width: 100%; padding: 8px; margin-bottom: 10px; }
    button { margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px 20px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Options</h1>
  <label for="apiKey">API Key:</label>
  <input type="text" id="apiKey" value="">
  <button id="saveBtn">Save</button>
  <script src="options.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

#### `options/options.js`

```javascript
// options/options.js

document.getElementById('saveBtn').addEventListener('click', () => {
  const apiKey = document.getElementById('apiKey').value;
  chrome.storage.sync.set({ apiKey }, () => {
    console.log('API Key saved');
  });
});

document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  // Load the saved API key from storage
  chrome.storage.sync.get('apiKey', (data) => {
    document.getElementById('apiKey').value = data.apiKey || '';
  });
});
```

### 6. Icons

Place your extension icons in the `icons` folder. Ensure you have at least `icon_48.png` and `icon_128.png` for the default and smaller icons.

### Conclusion

This guide provided a comprehensive introduction on how to build a basic Chrome extension that displays current weather information. The extension uses a service worker to fetch data, a content script for interaction, and HTML/JavaScript files for the user interface. This setup ensures a robust and modular architecture, which is important for creating scalable and maintainable extensions.

### Relevant Resources

To deepen your understanding, consider the following resources:

- [Chrome Extensions Documentation (Chromedocs)](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/extensions/mv3/overview/)
- [OpenWeatherMap API Documentation](https://openweathermap.org/api)
- [MDN Web Docs for Geolocation](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Geolocation_API)
- [Chrome Extension Samples](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/extensions/mv3/samples/)

---

This guide should help you get started on building Chrome extensions effectively. If you encounter any issues or have further questions, feel free to ask!

Certainly! Below is an example of a React component that uses the `react-query` library to fetch data from an API.

First, make sure you have `react` and `react-query` installed in your project. You can install them via npm or yarn:

```bash
npm install react react-query
# or
yarn add react react-query
```

Now, here's a simple example of a component that fetches data from an API using `react-query`:

```javascript
import React from 'react';
import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider, useQuery } from 'react-query';

// Create a client for `quer`y
const queryClient = new QueryClient();

const FetchData = () => {
  // Define the API endpoint
  const apiUrl = 'https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1';

  const { isLoading, isError, data, error } = useQuery('todos', () =>
    fetch(apiUrl).then(res => res.json())
  );

  if (isLoading) return 'Loading...';
  if (isError) return 'An error has occurred: ' + error.message;

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Fetched Data</h1>
      <p>Title: {data.title}</p>
      <p>Completed: {data.completed ? 'Yes' : 'No'}</p>
    </div>
  );
};

const App = () => (
  <QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
    <FetchData />
  </QueryClientProvider>
);

export default App;
```

### Explanation:

1. **Import React and React Query:**
   ```javascript
   import React from 'react';
   import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider, useQuery } from 'react-query';
   ```

2. **Create a Query Client:**
