shortest_response:
Certainly! Below is an example of a React component using `react-query` for fetching data from an API. In this example, we will create a simple component that fetches a list of users from an API.

First, make sure you have `react-query` installed in your project. You can install it using npm or yarn:

```bash
npm install react-query
# or
yarn add react-query
```

Now, let's create the component:

```jsx
// UserList.js
import React from 'react';
import { useQuery } from 'react-query';

const fetchUsers = async () => {
  const response = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users');
  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error('Network response was not ok');
  }
  return response.json();
};

const UserList = () => {
  const { isLoading, isError, data, error } = useQuery('users', fetchUsers);

  if (isLoading) return <div>Loading...</div>;
  if (isError) return <div>An error has occurred: {error.message}</div>;

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>List of Users</h1>
      <ul>
        {data.map(user => (
          <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}

export default UserList;
```

To use this component, you need to wrap your application or the component tree with the `QueryClientProvider` and provide it with a `QueryClient`:

```jsx
// App.js
import React from 'react';
import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider } from 'react-query';
import UserList from './UserList';

const queryClient = new QueryClient();

function App() {
  return (
    <QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
      <div className="App">
        <UserList />
      </div>
    </QueryClientProvider>
  );
}

export default App;
```

This setup uses `react-query` to handle data fetching, caching, synchronization, and other related issues. The `UserList` component makes a network request to fetch a list of users and displays them. It also handles different loading and error states effectively.

Make sure you handle API key if `jsonplaceholder.typicode.com` requires any and configure the `fetchUsers` function accordingly.

That's it! You now have a React component using `react-query` to fetch data from an API.

