longest_response:
It sounds like the issue is that FreeRADIUS is completing the authentication process before the MFA response is received. This can be caused by the `bash` script waiting for the BSA response or due to an incorrect configuration in the `authenticate` block.

To resolve this, you can try the following steps:

### Step 1: Ensure `wait = yes` is correct
You've already added `wait = yes`, which is correct. This ensures that FreeRADIUS will wait for the BSA response before continuing to the next step.

```r
exec bsa {
    wait = yes
    input_pairs = request
    output_pairs = reply
    program = "/usr/bin/java -cp /etc/freeradius/3.0/mods-available/bsa-authenticator/lib/* -Dlogback.configurationFile=/etc/freeradius/3.0/mods-available/bsa-authenticator/config/logback.xml -DbsaType=request -DbsaURL=https://example.com -DbsaClientKey=clientKey -DbsaID='%{User-Name}' com.app.auth.Authenticator"
    shell_escape = yes
    timeout = 30
}
```

And for `bsa_cancel`:

```r
exec bsa_cancel {
    wait = yes
    input_pairs = request
    output_pairs = reply
    program = "/usr/bin/java -cp /etc/freeradius/3.0/mods-available/bsa-authenticator/lib/* -Dlogback.configurationFile=/etc/freeradius/3.0/mods-available/bsa-authenticator/config/logback.xml -DbsaType=cancel -DbsaURL=https://example.com -DbsaClientKey=clientKey -DbsaID='%{User-Name}' com.app.auth.Authenticator"
    shell_escape = yes
    timeout = 30
}
```

### Step 2: Adjust the `authenticate` block
Make sure the `Auth-Type BSA` is correctly called within the LDAP section. You need to check the flow of requests and replies carefully to ensure that the BSA module is not being skipped. Here is an updated version of the `authenticate` and `post-auth` configurations:

#### Authenticate block

```r
authenticate {
    Auth-Type Default {
        reject
    }

    Auth-Type LDAP {
        ldap
    }

    Auth-Type BSA {
        bsa
    }
}
```

#### Post-auth block

You mentioned you've already added the `if else` blocks correctly, but let’s verify them:

```r
post-auth {
    Update request {
        Ldap-Group-Name := ${reply:Ldap-Group-Name}
        User-Geoposition := ${reply:User-Geoposition}
    }

    Update reply {
        Ldap-Group-Name := ${reply:Ldap-Group-Name} || "Unknown group name."
    }

    if (${reply:Auth-Type} == "Reject") {
        bsa {
            fail = 9
        }
        if (%{reply:Ldap-Group-Name} =~ /^cn=.*?,cn=.*?,ou=Client,dc=dev-ldap,dc=fnsmalaysia,dc=com$/) {
            Update reply {
                Ldap-Group-Name := "%1"
                Reply-Message := "%{reply:Reply-Message}"
            }
        } else {
            Update reply {
                Reply-Message := "Unknown group name."
            }
            reject
        }
    } elseif (%{reply:Auth-Type} == "MFA Required") {
        Update reply {
            Auth-Type := "%{reply:Auth-Type}"
        }
        reject
    } else {
        bsa_cancel
        reject
    }
}
```

### Step 3: Check the logs
After making these changes, thoroughly check the FreeRADIUS logs to see if there's any indication of where the process might be failing. These logs are typically located in `/var/log/freeradius`.

### Step 4: Debug logging
Enable debug logging in FreeRADIUS to get more detailed information about the authentication process. You can do this by editing the FreeRADIUS configuration and adding the following line to the `[radius]` section:

``` ini
log_dir = /var/log/freeradius
log_file = freeradius.log
log = debug
```

This will ensure you see detailed debugging information in `/var/log/freeradius/freeradius.log`.

### Final Step: Testing
After implementing these changes, test the authentication flow to see if the authentication is properly waiting for the MFA (BSA) response and providing the appropriate authentication result.

Lastly, ensure that your Java-based BSA module is functioning properly and is correctly configured to handle the input and output pairs. Any issues within the BSA module itself could also cause the incorrect behavior you're observing.

shortest_response:
The issue you're facing is likely due to the fact that the post-auth section in your FreeRADIUS configuration process all the checks immediately, without waiting for the second factor (BIOS) to complete for the first factor (LDAP) authentication to fully succeed.

To fix this, you should move your LDAP and BSA sections into a separate module, such as `authorize`. This way, FreeRADIUS will process these checks sequentially, waiting for each one to complete before proceeding to the next.

Modify your `default` configuration file as follows:

Add a new module for LDAP and BSA in the `authorize` section:

```shell
authorize {
    # LDAP and BSA
    Authorize {
        ldap
    }
    BSA {
        bsa
    }
}
```

Then, in your `post-auth` section, you can remove the LDAP and BSA logic and simply check the response from the module:

```shell
post-auth {
    # Process the response from the authorize module
    if (ok) {
        update request {
            User-Type := "%{User-Type}"
        }
        if (!&authenticated) {
            update reply {
                Reply-Message := "LDAP authentication failed."
            }
            reject
        }
    } else {
        update reply {
            Reply-Message := "LDAP authentication failed."
        }
        reject
    }
}
```

Now, FreeRADIUS will wait for the authorization to complete before proceeding with the post-authentication processing. Make sure to reload or restart your FreeRADIUS service to apply these changes:

```shell
systemctl reload freeradius
```

With these changes, FreeRADIUS should now wait for the LDAP and BSA processes to complete before proceeding to the post-authentication phase.

