Here's a simple example of how you can dynamically change the width of an iframe based on the viewport width using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Responsive Iframe</title>
<style>
  iframe {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 100%;
    height: 500px;
    border: none;
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<iframe src="https://html.com"></iframe>

<script>
  function changeIframeWidth() {
    const iframe = document.querySelector('iframe');
    const viewportWidth = window.innerWidth;
    let width = 360;

    if (viewportWidth < 360) {
      width = 360;
    } else if (viewportWidth < 720 && viewportWidth >= 360) {
      width = 720;
    } else if (viewportWidth < 1400 && viewportWidth >= 720) {
      width = 1400;
    } else {
      width = 1400;
    }

    iframe.style.width = `${width}px`;
  }

  // Initial iframe width
  changeIframeWidth();

  // Resize event listener
  window.addEventListener('resize', changeIframeWidth);
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the iframe width will change based on the viewport's width. The iframe will have a width of 360px if the viewport is less than 360px, 720px if the viewport is between 360px and 720px, and 1400px if the viewport is 720px or larger. The `resize` event listener ensures that the iframe width changes dynamically when the viewport size changes.

