Using Wistia Uploader in an Angular application involves several steps, including integrating the Wistia Uploader functionality, setting up API keys, and handling video uploads. Below is a step-by-step guide to help you get started with using Wistia Uploader in an Angular 14 application.

### Prerequisites

1. **Wistia Account**: Ensure you have a Wistia account with permission to upload videos.
2. **Wistia API Key**: Obtain your API key from the Wistia dashboard.
3. **Angular Project**: You should have an Angular project set up. If not, you can create one using:
   ```sh
   ng new my-wistia-app
   cd my-wistia-app
   ```

### Step 1: Install the Wistia Uploader Library

To use Wistia Uploader, you need to install the Wistia JavaScript SDK. You can do this using npm.

```sh
npm install wistia-js uploader
```

### Step 2: Set Up the Wistia Uploader in Angular

1. **Configure the Uploader in a Service or Component**

Create a service to handle the integration with the Wistia Uploader. For instance, you can create a service called `wistia-upload.service.ts`.

```typescript
// src/app/wistia-upload.service.ts
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import Wistia from 'wistia-js/uploader';

@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'
})
export class WistiaUploadService {
  private wistiaClient: any;

  constructor() {
    this.wistiaClient = Wistia.init({
      apiKey: 'YOUR_WISTIA_API_KEY_HERE'
    });
  }

  uploadVideo(mediaFile: File, title: string, metadata: any) {
    console.log("Uploading video...");

    this.wistiaClient.uploadVideo({
      file: mediaFile,
      title: title,
      description: 'Sample Video',
      tags: ['sample', 'test'],
      metadata: metadata,
      onSuccess: response => {
        console.log('Upload Success', response);
      },
      onError: error => {
        console.error('Upload Error', error);
      }
    });
  }
}
```

2. **Create a Component to Handle File Uploads**

Create a component where you can trigger the video upload process.

```typescript
// src/app/upload-video/upload-video.component.ts
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { WistiaUploadService } from '../wistia-upload.service';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-upload-video',
  templateUrl: './upload-video.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./upload-video.component.css']
})
export class UploadVideoComponent {
  videoFile: File | null = null;
  title = '';

  constructor(private wistiaService: WistiaUploadService) {}

  onFileChange(fileEvent: any) {
    this.videoFile = fileEvent.target.files[0];
  }

  onSubmit() {
    if (this.videoFile && this.videoFile.name) {
      this.wistiaService.uploadVideo(this.videoFile, this.title, {
        custom_field_1: 'example_field_value',
        custom_field_2: 'another_example'
      });
    }
  }
}
```

3. **HTML Template for the Upload Component**

Create an HTML template to render the file input and submit button.

```html
<!-- src/app/upload-video/upload-video.component.html -->
<div>
  <input type="file" (change)="onFileChange($event)" />
  <input type="text" placeholder="Video Title" [(ngModel)]="title" name="videoTitle" required />
  <button (click)="onSubmit()">Upload Video</button>
</div>
```

4. **Add the Component to App Module**

Make sure to add the upload component to your app module.

```typescript
// src/app/app.module.ts
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { BrowserModule } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { FormsModule } from '@angular/forms';

import { AppComponent } from './app.component';
import { UploadVideoComponent } from './upload-video/upload-video.component';

@NgModule({
  declarations: [
    AppComponent,
    UploadVideoComponent
  ],
  imports: [
    BrowserModule,
    FormsModule
  ],
  providers: [],
  bootstrap: [AppComponent]
})
export class AppModule { }
```

5. **Include the Component in the App Template**

Add the `UploadVideoComponent` to your main application template.

```html
<!-- src/app/app.component.html -->
<app-upload-video></app-upload-video>
```

### Step 3: Set Up Wistia API Key and Testing

Replace `YOUR_WISTIA_API_KEY_HERE` with your actual Wistia API key.

```typescript
this.wistiaClient = Wistia.init({
  apiKey: 'YOUR_WISTIA_API_KEY_HERE'
});
```

### Step 4: Test the Application

Run your Angular application and test the file upload functionality to ensure videos are uploaded correctly to your Wistia account.

```sh
ng serve
```

Visit `http://localhost:4200` in your browser, and you should be able to upload videos using the Wistia Uploader.

### Additional Considerations

- **Error Handling**: Enhance error handling to cover different scenarios like file size limitations, connection issues, etc.
- **Security**: Ensure you keep your API keys secure and never expose them in the client-side code. Consider using environment variables or other secure methods for managing keys.
- **Custom Fields and Metadata**: Customize the metadata sent with the videos as needed.

