Setting up a WordPress comment post API with authentication in a Next.js application involves several steps. Here’s a high-level guide to achieve this:

### Prerequisites:
1. **WordPress site:** Ensure you have a WordPress site with comments enabled.
2. **Next.js application:** Have a Next.js project set up.
3. **Node.js and npm/Yarn:** Needed to manage dependencies.

### Steps:

#### 1. Set Up WordPress REST API
WordPress has a built-in REST API that you can use to interact with comments programmatically. Make sure the REST API is enabled on your WordPress site.

#### 2. Install Axios
We'll use Axios to make HTTP requests in Next.js.

```bash
npm install axios
```

#### 3. Create API Route in Next.js
Create an API route in the `pages` directory to handle the comment posting.

**pages/api/submit-comment.js**
```javascript
import axios from 'axios';

const COMMENTS_URL = 'https://your-wordpress-site.com/wp-json/wp/v2/comments';
const AUTH_URL = 'https://your-wordpress-site.com/wp-json/jwt-auth/v1/token';

export default async function handler(req, res) {
  if (req.method === 'POST') {
    const { content } = req.body;

    const response = await axios.post(AUTH_URL, {
      username: 'yourusername',
      password: 'yourpassword',
    });

    const authToken = response.data.token;

    await axios.post(COMMENTS_URL, {
      author: 'your-wordpress-username',
      author_email: 'your-email@example.com',
      author_name: 'Your Name',
      content,
    }, {
      headers: {
        'Authorization': `Bearer ${authToken}`,
      },
    }).then(response => {
      res.status(200).json(response.data);
    }).catch(error => {
      res.status(500).json({ error: 'Error posting comment' });
    });
  } else {
    res.status(405).json({ error: 'Method not allowed' });
  }
}
```

Replace `'https://your-wordpress-site.com'`, `'yourusername'`, `'yourpassword'`, and email information with your actual WordPress site details.

#### 4. Frontend Form to Post Comment
Create a form in your Next.js application to send comments using the API route.

**components/CommentForm.js**
```javascript
import { useState } from 'react';

const CommentForm = () => {
  const [content, setContent] = useState('');
  const [error, setError] = useState('');

  const handleSubmit = async (event) => {
    event.preventDefault();
    setError('');

    const res = await fetch('/api/submit-comment', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: {
        'Content-Type': 'application/json',
      },
      body: JSON.stringify({ content }),
    });

    if (res.ok) {
      // Clear form
      setContent('');
    } else {
      setError('Error posting comment');
    }
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <textarea
        value={content}
        onChange={(e) => setContent(e.target.value)}
        placeholder="Write a comment..."
        required
      />
      <button type="submit">Post Comment</button>
      {error && <p className="error">{error}</p>}
    </form>
  );
};

export default CommentForm;
```

#### 5. Use the Form Component in Your Page
Import and use the `CommentForm` component in your Next.js page.

**pages/index.js**
```javascript
import CommentForm from '../components/CommentForm';

const HomePage = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>WordPress Comments in Next.js</h1>
      <CommentForm />
    </div>
  );
};

export default HomePage;
```

### Summary
1. **Set up REST API on WordPress.**
2. **Install Axios for HTTP requests.**
3. **Create an API route in Next.js to handle comment posting.**
4. **Create a front-end form to submit comments to the API.**
5. **Integrate the form into your Next.js pages.**

This setup allows you to authenticate and post comments from your Next.js application to your WordPress site using the REST API.

