To display an error message when the DVD title is empty and the category is null, you can use a simple approach of showing a hidden error message with some conditional logic. Here's how you can modify your existing JavaScript code to show the error message:

First, add an error message element in your HTML file:

```html
<!-- Error message -->
<div id="error-message" style="display: none; color: red;">Please enter a DVD title and select a category.</div>
```

Then, make the following changes to your JavaScript code to display the error message:

```javascript
$(document).ready(function () {
    $("#create-post-form").submit(function (e) {
        e.preventDefault();

        var dvdTitle = $("#dvdTitle").val();
        var maxPrice = $("#maxPrice").val();
        var category = $("#exampleSelect").val();

        // Hide the error message initially
        $("#error-message").hide();

        if (maxPrice == "" && category == null) {
            // Show error message if both DVD title and category are empty
            if (dvdTitle == "" && category == "") {
                $("#error-message").text("Please enter a DVD title and select a category.");
                $("#error-message").show();
                return; // Prevent further execution of the ajax call
            }

            $.ajax({
                type: "GET",
                url: "http://localhost:8081/filmtitle",
                data: {
                    dvdTitle: dvdTitle,
                },
                success: function (data) {
                    sessionStorage.setItem("searchResults", JSON.stringify(data));
                    window.location.assign("searchResults.html");
                }
            });
        } else {
            $.ajax({
                type: "GET",
                url: "http://localhost:8081/categoryname",
                data: {
                    dvdTitle: dvdTitle,
                    maxPrice: maxPrice,
                    category: category
                },
                success: function (data) {
                    sessionStorage.setItem("searchResults", JSON.stringify(data));
                    window.location.assign("searchResults.html");
                }
            });
        }
    });
});
```

In this modified code, we first check if both `dvdTitle` and `category` are empty. If they are, we show the error message and prevent the AJAX call from executing by returning from the function. If `dvdTitle` is not empty or the category is not null, we proceed with the AJAX call as before.

